The Arcadian and Athenian rites and legends suggest that before Homer, Artemis was a nature goddess. In her earlier form she roamed the wilds rather than chased wild animals. <br>
<br>
Artemis was born by 25,000 BCE to the north of Greece, but her cult did not come to Greece until about 1500 BCE. Around 125 AD her cult died in Greece and she was no longer worshipped there. <br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
Symbols of Artemis<br>
A number of wild animals are sacred to her: hind, bear, boar, goat, zebu, and lion. She is often shown with bow and arrow, mural crown, and a torch. In the classical period she is shown with the crescent moon in her hair. <br>
<br>
Robert Graves says that the silver fir is a female tree with leaves closely resembling the yew's, sacred in Greece to Artemis, the Moon-goddess who presided over childbirth, and it is the prime birth-tree of Northern Europe. He also says that cranes were sacred to Artemis. <br>
<br>
